{
  "doc_id": "42867",
  "text": "In the present study, we investigated the expression of IL-23 during the course of clinical disease in active EAN by exploring the presence of its unique p19 subunit. We found a striking up-regulation of IL-23p19 RNA prior to the onset of clinical symptoms at day 11 PI with peak expression levels at day 13 PI preceding maximum clinical disease severity. This differential expression pattern of IL-23p19 on the messenger level strongly points to a potential biological role of this cytokine in the early phase of the disease, suggesting an initiating role rather than a perpetuating role in the disease process in EAN. Our observation is in line with previous studies in the inflamed central nervous system. In EAE, IL-23p19 RNA was found to be dramatically induced prior to the peak of clinical disease activity and to decline thereafter, [CITATION_1] underlining the potential pathogenetic relevance of IL-23 in the early phases of immune-mediated demyelination of the nervous system. Moreover, IL-23-deficient mice were reported to be resistant to EAE. [CITATION_2] Thus, in EAN the expression pattern of IL-23 differs dramatically from the one reported for IL-12, the latter found to be predominantly up-regulated in the late effector phase of the disease. [CITATION_3] Interleukin 23, which comprises the p40 subunit of IL-12 but a different p19 subunit, [CITATION_4] has been proposed to exhibit similar but not overlapping functions with IL-12, such as inducing the production of IFN-␥ and T helper-1 cell differentiation. 2,3 Unlike IL-12, which is preferentially affecting naive T lymphocytes, IL-23 selectively induces the proliferation of memory T cells [CITATION_5] and their production of IFN-␥, [CITATION_6] ,33 a cytokine exhibiting multiple proinflammatory effects in the process of immunemediated demyelination of the inflamed peripheral nerve. [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] The temporospatial expression patterns of IFN-␥ and IL-12 RNAs have been substantially examined in EAN using semiquantitative RT-PCR. [CITATION_9] Whereas IL-12 RNA was found to be up-regulated during the recovery phase of EAN, IFN-␥ RNA levels did not parallel the expression of IL-12 with maximum levels being observed during the onset and the acute phase of clinical disease in EAN. [CITATION_10] Furthermore, immunohistochemistry revealed abundant IFN-␥-positive T cells to be present in active EAN before overt clinical signs and demyelination and to disappear at later stages when most of the axons were demyelinated. [CITATION_11] Thus, IFN-␥ induction in early EAN seems to occur in the absence of active IL-12. However, this discrepant expression of IFN-␥ and IL-12 may be explained by our finding that IL-23 is up-regulated during the onset and the acute phase of clinical disease activity in EAN, paralleling the reported appearance of IFN-␥. We believe that, at least partly, IL-23 may induce the expression of IFN-␥ during the early phase of EAN. On the other hand, no early up-regulation of the p40 subunit has been reported so far. This may be due to a lack of sensitivity or other technical restraints. Recent data suggest that IL-23 induces a specific cytokine pattern, distinct from IL-12, in activated human naive T lymphocytes. Interleukin 23 could induce IFN-␥ production in resting naive T cells within short time. [CITATION_12] These results strengthen the concept of a critical role of IL-23 during the early phase of the disease, where naive T cells are likely to be more abundant than memory cells. A different study suggested that IL-23 promotes a T-cell population characterized by the production of IL-17, tumor necrosis factor ␣, and IL-6 and that this IL-23-dependent T-cell subset invades and promotes the development of organspecific autoimmune inflammation. [CITATION_13] This pathway appears independent of IFN-␥, and the authors proposed an interplay between IL-23 and IL-17, potentially regulated via an IL-12-induced IFN-␥ pathway. [CITATION_14] It is obvious that further studies are needed to address this issue in greater detail and to elucidate the functional interaction between IFN-␥ and IL-23.",
